0000,"records":2},{"category":"consumer protection violation","penalty":695000,"records":2},{"category":"workplace safety or health violation","penalty":52547,"records":5},{"category":"insurance violation","penalty":35000,"records":1}],"rating":"good"}},"competitors":["best-buy","target","walmart","amazon"],"wiki":{"founded":"1980-08-20","hq":"Grapevine","employees":null,"revenue":"5272800000","parent":"Barnes & Noble","industry":"retail","products":null,"keyPeople":null,"website":"https://www.gamestop.com/","controversies":"==Controversies==\n=== Lawsuit against BCG ===\nIn 2022, consulting firm BCG filed a lawsuit against GameStop as the latter allegedly denied payment of fee worth $30 million for a project. GameStop argued that it saw it is in the best interest of its stakeholders to deny payment as BCG brought little improvement to the EBITDA of the company, which the consultancy allegedly promised to improve. BCG counter argued that the company has delivered more than it promised in statement of proposal and that the quoted variable fee was based on the \"projected\", not realised, improvement in EBITDA, as per the contract.\n\nUltimately, it turned out that BCG's lawsuit lacked the merit to be carried out in court. GameStop's claim about BCG not having delivered any value and not being owed any money for their supposed \"services\" was not controversial after all, and the lawsuit regarding these matters was dismissed with prejudice.\n\n=== Nintendo Switch 2 launch day incident ===\nOn June 5, 2025, a GameStop store in Staten Island, New York had stapled pre-order receipts to the boxes of Nintendo Switch 2 consoles for release day customers. Due to the way the console was packed near the front of the box, the staples were able to puncture the screens. GameStop immediately replaced the affected units and later held an auction for the stapler and a stapled console, since repaired, to raise money for the Children's Miracle Network Hospitals.","logoUrl":null,"wikipediaUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GameStop","extract":"GameStop Corp. is an American video game, consumer electronics, and gaming merchandise retailer, headquartered in Grapevine, Texas. The brand is the largest video game retailer worldwide. As of January 2026, the company operated 2,206 stores including 1,598 both in the United States, 300 in Australia and 308 in Europe under the GameStop, EB Games, Micromania-Zing, ThinkGeek and Zing Pop Culture brands. The company was founded in Dallas in 1984 as Babbage's, and took on its current name in 1999."},"bbb":{"rating":"F","accredited":null,"complaintCount":null,"profileUrl":"https://www.bbb.org/us/il/peru/profile/games/gamestop-0654-1000106541"},"secComplaints":{"count":2,"sample":[{"adsh":"0001326380-26-000007","date":"2026-01-08","filer":"GameStop Corp.  (GME, GME-WT)  (CIK 0001326380)","form":"8-K"},{"adsh":"0001193125-26-204193","date":"2026-05-04","filer":"Turtle Beach Corp  (TBCH)  (CIK 0001493761)","form":"8-K"}]},"payRatio":{"ratio":101,"ratioDisplay":"101:1","ceoPay":1754976,"medianWorkerPay":17376,"year":"2026","sourceForm":"DEF 14A","filedDate":"2026-05-22","sourceUrl":"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1326380/000119312526235130/d937376ddef14a.htm"},"logoUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/GameStop%20Logo%20(2000%E2%80%932012).svg","logoSource":"wikidata_p154","storeFootprint":{"usStoreCount":1765,"byState":{"TX":59,"PA":50,"IL":50,"CA":43,"OH":32,"NY":30,"AZ":27,"VA":27,"FL":23,"NC":20,"NJ":18,"OR":17,"CO":15,"MD":15,"WI":15,"IN":14,"AL":14,"WA":14,"UT":12,"MI":11,"GA":10,"MO":9,"MA":8,"MS":8,"KY":7,"OK":7,"NV":7,"KS":7,"TN":6,"NM":6,"SC":5,"LA":5,"DE":4,"IA":4,"ID":4,"NH":4,"ME":4,"AR":3,"CT":3,"NE":3,"MN":2,"SD":1,"RI":1,"WV":1,"WY":1,"MT":1}},"deiBadges":[{"scoreType":"hrc_cei","score":60,"year":2025,"sourceUrl":"https://hrc-prod-requests.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Report-Design-Graphics/CEI-images/CEI-2024/CEI-2025-Appendix-A-Company-6.pdf"}],"slug":"gamestop","news":